To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command named "ban," follow these steps. First, make sure you have Node.js installed and create a new project folder. Then, install the Discord.js library using npm:

```bash
mkdir discord-bot
cd discord-bot
npm init -y
npm install discord.js
```

Create a `index.js` file in the project folder and add the following code:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const client = new Discord.Client();

// Replace with your bot token from the Discord Developer Portal
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN_HERE';

client.on('ready', () => {
    console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

// Slash command for banning a user
client.slashCommands.interactions('ban', {
    name: 'ban',
    description: 'Ban a user from the server.',
    options: [
        {
            name: 'user',
            description: 'The user to ban.',
            type: 'USER',
            required: true,
        },
    ],
    async execute(interaction) {
        const user = interaction.user;
        if (!user) return interaction.reply('Invalid user!');

        try {
            await interaction.member.ban(user);
            interaction.reply(`Banned ${user.username} successfully.`);
        } catch (error) {
            interaction.reply('Failed to ban the user. Please try again.');
        }
    },
});

client.login(token);
```

Replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN_HERE'` with your actual bot token, which you can obtain from the Discord Developer Portal.

This code sets up a simple Discord bot with a single slash command, "ban." The command takes a single argument, "user," which represents the user to be banned. When executed, it will ban the user from the server and send a confirmation message to the Discord chat.

To run the bot, execute the following command in your terminal:

```bash
node index.js
```

Now, your bot is ready to use! You can invite it to your server by pasting the following link in a server's invite section:

```https://discord.com/api/oauth2/authorize?client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&permissions=8&scope=bot
```

Replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID` with the ID you get from the `client` object in your `index.js` file.

To create a high-quality testing framework using Cypress, Docker, and screenshot capture, follow these steps. First, set up your environment, then install the required packages, and finally, create a test file structure.

1. **Environment Setup**
- Install Node.js and npm (Node Package Manager) if not already installed.
- Install Cypress: `npm install cypress`
- Install Docker (if not already installed): `brew install docker` (for macOS) or `sudo apt-get install docker.io` (for Ubuntu/Debian)
- Add Docker to your PATH (macOS) or `sudo docker --gpus all run -it --rm cypress/included` (Linux) to start a development container.

2. **Create a `cypress/support` folder**
- Inside this folder, create a `commands.js` file for custom commands.
- Create a `docker-compose.yml` file for managing the test environment (optional, but useful for complex setups).

3. **`commands.js`**
```javascript
// cypress/support/commands.js
Cypress.Commands.add('runDocker', async (command, options = {}) => {
  // Start a Docker container for the test environment
  await cy.task('docker:start', { command, options });
  // Wait for the container to be ready
  await cy.wait('@docker:ready');
  // Stop the container after the test
  await cy.task('docker:stop');
});

Cypress.Commands.add('docker:start', { command: 'your-command', options: { /* your options */ } }, { prevSubject: 'viewport' });
Cypress.Commands.add('docker:ready', { subject: 'viewport' }, { timeout: 10000 }); // Adjust the timeout as needed
Cypress.Commands.add('docker:stop', { subject: 'viewport' });
```
4. **`docker-compose.yml` (optional)**
```yaml
# cypress/support/docker-compose.yml
version: '3'
services:
  your-command:
    image: your-test-environment-image
    command: your-command
    ports:
      - "3000:3000" (or your port mapping)
    environment:
      - YOUR_VARIABLE=your-value
```
5. **`cypress/integration` folder**
- Create a folder for your feature files, e.g., `e2e-tests`.
- Inside this folder, create a `index.js` file for the root test file.
- Use the `runDocker` command in your feature files to set up and tear down the Docker environment.

6. **`index.js` (root test file)**
```javascript
// cypress/integration/index.js
describe('Your Feature', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    cy.runDocker('your-command', { // Replace with your command and options
      // If using docker-compose.yml, pass the service name
    });
  });

  // Your test cases
  it('should do something', () => {
    // Your test steps
    cy.viewport(1920, 1080);
    cy.takeScreenshot({ filename: 'example-screenshot.png' }); // Capture a screenshot
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    cy.runDocker('docker:stop');
  });
});
```
7. **Running tests**
- Start your development container: `docker run -it --rm cypress/included`
- Open a terminal in the project directory and run `cypress run` to execute the tests.

This setup will create a Cypress testing framework that leverages Docker for setting up test environments, captures screenshots, and saves them in the `cypress/screenshots` directory by default. You can customize the commands, options, and environment variables as per your specific use case.

Sure! Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing HTML formatted text using the `pandoc` library. Note that you'll need to install the `pandoc` library and link it to your project for this to work. For simplicity, I'll assume you have the `pandoc-cpp` library installed.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <pandocfilters.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    try {
        // Create a Pandoc filter to convert Markdown to HTML
        pcrecpp::RegEx re("#.*$"); // Remove headers
        auto filter = Pandocfilters::createFilter(
            Pandocfilters::Filter::Reader,
            Pandocfilters::Filter::Writer,
            Pandocfilters::Filter::H,
            Pandocfilters::Filter::Inlines,
            Pandocfilters::Filter::RawBlock,
            Pandocfilters::Filter::Str,
            [re](const std::string& name, const std::vector<std::string>& args, void* data) -> bool {
                if (name == "Header") {
                    if (re.hasMatch(args[0])) {
                        return false; // Remove headers
                    }
                }
                return true;
            },
            nullptr
        );

        // Convert Markdown to HTML using Pandoc filters
        filter->processMarkdown(markdown, &html);

        // Print the HTML string
        std::cout << "HTML: " << html << std::endl;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Error converting Markdown to HTML: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        return "";
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello, **world!** This is a sample **markdown** text.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    if (html.empty()) {
        std::cout << "Failed to convert Markdown." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "HTML: " << html << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we create a Pandoc filter that removes headers from the Markdown text. Then, we use the `processMarkdown` function to convert the Markdown to HTML. Note that you'll need to link your project to the `pandoc-cpp` library.

Make sure to replace the `pcrecpp` header with `pcre2cpp` if you're using a newer version of `pandoc-cpp`. Also, if you don't have `pandoc-cpp` installed, you can use a third-party library like `markdown-cpp` or implement the conversion manually using regular expressions or a library like `libmarkdown`.

